WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:11.000
Ladies and gentlemen, friends of Tennessee, I'm very happy to have with me today in the

00:11.000 --> 00:18.520
studio one of the finest members of the United States Senate, man who works hard for progressive

00:18.520 --> 00:26.120
legislation who is effective in his presentation of legislative proposals and of his viewpoint.

00:26.120 --> 00:32.240
He has been to Tennessee on many occasions and we consider him one of our Tennessee's

00:32.240 --> 00:38.480
and best friends and I think one of the very ablest members of the Senate, Wayne Morris

00:38.480 --> 00:39.480
of Oregon.

00:39.480 --> 00:40.960
It certainly is good to have you with us.

00:40.960 --> 00:45.960
Well, that's just very kind to let me visit with you and your constituents on this program.

00:45.960 --> 00:49.440
You can close your ears for just a moment because I know you're a modest man.

00:49.440 --> 00:51.480
Well, I want to send you your constituents.

00:51.480 --> 00:57.880
It's a privilege to work with us as Keith Offer in the Senate and I want to thank him and

00:57.880 --> 01:02.800
view of his constituents for the wonderful help he was to me a few days ago as we carried

01:02.800 --> 01:09.080
through the Senate by a vote of 49 to 34, the federal aid education bill.

01:09.080 --> 01:13.160
As Keith Offer was a great help to me, it's a bill that's going to be of great help to

01:13.160 --> 01:18.920
Tennessee because you're going to get a substantial contribution from the federal government

01:18.920 --> 01:24.800
to be of assistance in your schools but with complete state control of the expenditure

01:24.800 --> 01:25.800
of the money.

01:25.800 --> 01:28.800
Well, Wayne, thank you very much for your nice remarks.

01:28.800 --> 01:33.560
You've been not as thoughtful going down to Knoxville and other places in Tennessee making

01:33.560 --> 01:38.840
speeches to our people on several occasions.

01:38.840 --> 01:43.240
Senator Morris is a member of the Labor and Public Works Committee and is chairman of

01:43.240 --> 01:46.000
the Education Subcommittee.

01:46.000 --> 01:51.960
And I think one of the best legislative handling of a bill that I have seen, but ever since

01:51.960 --> 01:57.400
I've been in the United States Senate, was the remarkable way that he steered the education

01:57.400 --> 02:02.640
bill through the United States Senate recently without any crippling amendments involving

02:02.640 --> 02:10.720
either race or religion, got through a fine clean bill which is now in the House of Representatives.

02:10.720 --> 02:18.080
This bill, I believe, provides $850 million a year for school construction and to supplement

02:18.080 --> 02:21.200
teachers salaries over a three-year period.

02:21.200 --> 02:22.200
Is that right?

02:22.200 --> 02:23.200
Yes, that's the system.

02:23.200 --> 02:26.760
$850 million per year bill.

02:26.760 --> 02:31.160
And it's child bill for three years or triad for three years.

02:31.160 --> 02:36.080
I'm satisfied that after three years the American people will insist that it be continued.

02:36.080 --> 02:40.880
But you know, as to say, the fear argument that's been used for so long against federal

02:40.880 --> 02:46.280
aid to education is that you can't have federal contributions to the states without the federal

02:46.280 --> 02:49.480
government somehow dominating education.

02:49.480 --> 02:54.720
Now there's no basis in that argument, but as long as the fear exists, you got to face

02:54.720 --> 02:56.080
up to the fear.

02:56.080 --> 03:00.040
So we have passed a bill that's for a three-year trial period.

03:00.040 --> 03:05.680
It is a bill that has an equalization formula in it, which simply means that the states that

03:05.680 --> 03:09.960
need the money the most will get the larger share of the money.

03:09.960 --> 03:12.240
And why do we put it on that basis?

03:12.240 --> 03:18.280
Because we take the position that every boy and girl in this country is entitled to an

03:18.280 --> 03:22.680
equal chance to develop his or her intellectual power.

03:22.680 --> 03:26.400
And that's where the national interest comes in.

03:26.400 --> 03:29.040
Now, how do we protect the states?

03:29.040 --> 03:34.080
We protect the states by making it perfectly clear in the bill that the money goes to the

03:34.080 --> 03:40.800
states is co-mingled with state educational funds is spent by the states and the cardinance

03:40.800 --> 03:42.680
with state educational policy.

03:42.680 --> 03:46.440
Now, I've been in this struggle for many, many years in the Senate.

03:46.440 --> 03:49.000
I've been in the Senate now going on 17 years.

03:49.000 --> 03:55.600
I was a co-sponsor of the Taff Bill in 47 of the Taff Thompson Bill in 49.

03:55.600 --> 03:57.800
We passed both of those through the Senate.

03:57.800 --> 04:01.880
I've introduced these bills year after year since I've been in the Senate.

04:01.880 --> 04:07.680
And last year, we passed what is known as Senate Bill number eight.

04:07.680 --> 04:12.440
It is almost identical with the bill that we just passed the other day in the Senate.

04:12.440 --> 04:13.440
I want to make one more point.

04:13.440 --> 04:15.240
I don't want to make speech as this one.

04:15.240 --> 04:17.240
You're doing fine with how to explain this.

04:17.240 --> 04:22.560
I want to tell you, people in Tennessee are very much interested in this bill.

04:22.560 --> 04:28.520
And I think the great majority of people realize that we need it in Tennessee.

04:28.520 --> 04:35.440
It will make available $23,500,000 for school construction and to supplement teacher

04:35.440 --> 04:37.800
salvers in the next fiscal year in Tennessee.

04:37.800 --> 04:39.840
So you're making a fine speech.

04:39.840 --> 04:40.840
You go right on that.

04:40.840 --> 04:46.480
Well, another one that covers school construction and teacher salaries, but you can also use it

04:46.480 --> 04:52.480
for any other educational purpose in public, elementary and secondary schools.

04:52.480 --> 04:57.520
For example, if you need to use it for equipment in your physics and chemistry laboratories,

04:57.520 --> 04:59.520
it can be used for that purpose too.

04:59.520 --> 05:02.680
We leave that decision up to you at the state.

05:02.680 --> 05:09.640
But let me point out that I think the argument that helps us defeat those that keep stirring

05:09.640 --> 05:14.960
up opposition to federal aid to education with the false charge that it will lead to federal

05:14.960 --> 05:16.440
domination of schools.

05:16.440 --> 05:24.200
So we pointed out that one third of the children in secondary and elementary schools in the

05:24.200 --> 05:31.080
country have been getting federal aid for 10 years and to the tune of two billions of

05:31.080 --> 05:32.240
dollars.

05:32.240 --> 05:37.600
All of us as taxpayers have contributed to about a third of the public school population

05:37.600 --> 05:42.680
in this country and elementary and secondary schools, two billion dollars.

05:42.680 --> 05:46.960
Under what is known is public law 874 and 815.

05:46.960 --> 05:52.400
Those are the two bills that cover the so-called federally impacted areas of the country,

05:52.400 --> 05:57.400
and the federal government has an atomic energy plant or a military reservation or some

05:57.400 --> 06:04.320
other federal installation that brings in many families working for the federal government

06:04.320 --> 06:06.160
with many children.

06:06.160 --> 06:08.160
And then we have Spence and...

06:08.160 --> 06:13.080
Well, in that connection we have a great many military installations in Tennessee, Oak

06:13.080 --> 06:14.080
Ridge, Tallahoma.

06:14.080 --> 06:15.080
Oh, yes.

06:15.080 --> 06:21.080
And may I say that the Senator Keith Offer was on the ball, so to speak, because the

06:21.080 --> 06:26.080
original bill that came before us, and I had this always unpleasant when you have to

06:26.080 --> 06:31.080
disagree with your administration, I had the unpleasant task of informing the administration

06:31.080 --> 06:35.160
that we would not accept that section of the original proposal of the administration

06:35.160 --> 06:40.880
bill that sought to cut back drastically on these school districts that are now receiving

06:40.880 --> 06:44.360
federal funds in the federally impacted area.

06:44.360 --> 06:47.400
18 Senators and your Senator was one of them.

06:47.440 --> 06:52.400
18 Senators called our attention to the fact that it would do a great injustice to their

06:52.400 --> 06:55.280
states, so we struck that from the bill.

06:55.280 --> 07:00.880
And we continue under this bill to provide this federal money for these federally impacted

07:00.880 --> 07:01.880
school districts.

07:01.880 --> 07:05.680
But then I want to take you back to 1863.

07:05.680 --> 07:14.640
In 1863, the Moral Act was signed, which provided federal aids to every land grant

07:14.640 --> 07:15.640
college in America.

07:15.640 --> 07:21.080
You people in Tennessee have been the beneficiaries of that, to the tune of tens upon tens of

07:21.080 --> 07:25.560
thousands of dollars to your land grant colleges, as there's every other state.

07:25.560 --> 07:30.360
And then we've had a whole series of other special forms of aid to the schools of the

07:30.360 --> 07:32.200
country for years.

07:32.200 --> 07:35.840
So what we, well, we got their school lunch program.

07:35.840 --> 07:38.560
School lunch program is another example of it.

07:38.560 --> 07:43.680
So we just, we just rode on this argument, so to speak.

07:43.680 --> 07:48.960
And the Senate, once it got the facts, saw that there was no basis in fact for the argument

07:48.960 --> 07:52.120
that our bill would jeopardize local control of education.

07:52.120 --> 07:53.880
I'm proud of this bill.

07:53.880 --> 07:57.560
I'm proud of the wonderful support that we got for our bill.

07:57.560 --> 08:00.400
And I again want to thank Senator Kiefer for his help.

08:00.400 --> 08:02.680
Well, that was a great legislative achievement.

08:02.680 --> 08:06.480
And you were the Generalissimo guiding us in the Senate.

08:06.480 --> 08:11.880
And I have a feeling that such a good record was made and your arguments were so persuasive

08:11.880 --> 08:16.400
in favor of this bill that we have the best chance of getting a bill through the House

08:16.400 --> 08:18.800
of Representatives we've had in many, many years.

08:18.800 --> 08:19.800
How do you feel about that?

08:19.800 --> 08:21.960
Well, I'm very hopeful that we can get it through the House.

08:21.960 --> 08:27.120
And if the people listening to this telecast want to help the schoolboys and girls of

08:27.120 --> 08:33.440
this country, see to it that your House representative's no-year views on it because I close my

08:33.440 --> 08:39.320
comment of this education bill with a truism I'd have you never forget.

08:39.320 --> 08:45.480
I consider this bill a great defense measure because as I've said so many times, but we'll

08:45.480 --> 08:50.160
keep right on saying it until all the American people recognize it's truth.

08:50.160 --> 08:54.520
We just can't keep ahead of Russia in manpower.

08:54.520 --> 09:00.440
But we Americans better see to it that we keep ahead of Russia in brainpower.

09:00.440 --> 09:06.600
And that's why we need this federal aid education bill to help you people in the states meet

09:06.600 --> 09:09.960
your educational responsibilities because how you're doing it now.

09:09.960 --> 09:13.480
You're doing it by overtaxing your real property.

09:13.480 --> 09:19.320
And many taxpayer listening to me who owns real property knows how right I am.

09:19.320 --> 09:25.840
We've already increased the taxes on real property to support our schools far below

09:25.840 --> 09:29.160
beyond the role of fairness.

09:29.160 --> 09:34.360
It's about time that we get some tax help from the federal government that will help the

09:34.360 --> 09:38.960
local taxpayer meet the school expenses of this district.

09:38.960 --> 09:43.240
Well I wish we could go on about the education bill because it is so very important for

09:43.240 --> 09:49.400
all of us and we're certainly going to work hard to do what we can to get it through the

09:49.400 --> 09:55.800
House of Representatives and I hope that anyone interested may be in touch with our congressman.

09:55.800 --> 10:02.560
But you know Senator Morris is a distinguished and has been for some time a member of the

10:02.560 --> 10:04.200
Foreign Relations Committee.

10:04.200 --> 10:09.560
And as such he is the chairman of the Latin American Subcommittee.

10:09.560 --> 10:15.120
In addition to this he has was the member of the United States delegation to the 15th

10:15.120 --> 10:18.200
General Assembly of the United Nations.

10:18.200 --> 10:22.440
We're all interested way in and don't have the benefit of hearing the executive testimony

10:22.440 --> 10:27.760
before the Foreign Relations Committee and how we stand in Latin America and what can

10:27.760 --> 10:33.920
we do to restore our prestige and get in better shape with our neighbors to the south of

10:33.920 --> 10:34.920
us.

10:34.920 --> 10:39.200
Well as to I wish I could report that in my opinion we stand high but we don't.

10:39.200 --> 10:45.200
I don't suppose our prestige has been lower in Latin America at any time in the last 20

10:45.200 --> 10:49.360
years and it has been during the last few years.

10:49.360 --> 10:53.200
I think our policy has been very bad in Latin America.

10:53.200 --> 10:59.220
I speak most respectfully and non-partisanly but factually when I point out that the Latin

10:59.220 --> 11:05.760
American program of the preceding administration is chief cause I think for the great slump

11:05.760 --> 11:08.800
in Latin American U.S. relations.

11:08.800 --> 11:14.400
We've got to stop U.S. unilateral action toward Latin America.

11:14.400 --> 11:19.800
We've got to adopt a program and present Kennedy's program now called Alliance Progress

11:19.800 --> 11:22.760
will accomplish that end if it's implemented.

11:22.760 --> 11:28.960
We've got to get our friends in Latin America to join with us in a cooperative Latin American

11:28.960 --> 11:29.960
program.

11:29.960 --> 11:36.360
And that means of course that the organization of American states which is based upon a treaty

11:36.360 --> 11:42.080
signed by 21 nations including us has really got to be implemented.

11:42.080 --> 11:47.280
And we've got to bring in our friends in Latin America to join with us in developing

11:47.280 --> 11:50.400
a Latin American program on a cooperative basis.

11:50.400 --> 11:55.600
And we've got to stop taking the attitudes that we the United States are going to call

11:55.600 --> 11:57.240
the tune in Latin America.

11:57.240 --> 12:02.560
Well we're not going to do it even if we try because if we continue to follow the policy

12:02.560 --> 12:07.120
we've been following in Cuba and no one has opposed cast through more than I have.

12:07.120 --> 12:12.000
I have led the fight in the Senate as chairman of the subcommittee in Latin America against

12:12.000 --> 12:17.760
the cast through regime because I'm perfectly convinced that it's a comeline regime and

12:17.760 --> 12:22.680
that Moscow is dictating in large measure the policies of Castro.

12:22.680 --> 12:27.240
But that doesn't justify unilateral action on the part of the United States.

12:27.240 --> 12:33.920
And so I am urging that we go through the organization of American states and work

12:33.920 --> 12:35.920
out a cooperative program with them.

12:35.920 --> 12:40.920
As you know Estes I was one of the two congressional delegates to the Bogota conference last

12:40.920 --> 12:44.640
September that came back with the act of Bogota.

12:44.640 --> 12:51.240
The act of Bogota is an aid program or proposes an aid program for Latin America with United

12:51.240 --> 12:53.000
States help.

12:53.000 --> 12:57.800
But not with full payment for the United States and I want to very quickly say we have said

12:57.800 --> 13:01.280
very clearly and we must make it clear to Latin America.

13:01.280 --> 13:05.120
We'll help Latin America if Latin America is willing to help itself.

13:05.120 --> 13:08.920
Now you say Mr. Senator what must Latin America do to get our help?

13:08.920 --> 13:11.600
Well I want to name a few things very quickly.

13:11.600 --> 13:16.400
You know the main past time in Latin America is tax evasion.

13:16.400 --> 13:18.720
The Latin Americans are going to have to pay taxes.

13:18.720 --> 13:21.720
They're going to have to raise money to help themselves.

13:21.720 --> 13:25.560
They got to have a program of land reform, social justice reform.

13:25.560 --> 13:30.400
That's the kind of a program that the president Kennedy is supporting and that I endorse.

13:30.400 --> 13:36.440
Well you know I know the people who are viewing this program feel as I do that they're

13:36.440 --> 13:38.560
awfully sorry that has to be brought to an end.

13:38.560 --> 13:43.840
It's been very fine of you to come and come down to Tennessee to see us soon and thank

13:43.840 --> 13:44.840
you very much.

13:44.840 --> 13:45.840
Thank you very much.

13:45.840 --> 13:46.840
Thank you.

13:46.840 --> 13:47.840
That's all for now ladies and gentlemen.

